I am¬†glad to have time off¬†to rediscover and find peace with myself @ Banyan Tree Wellbeing Sanctuary. This experience has inspired me to look inward and become more aware of my daily actions, thoughts, and emotions. 

It is difficult to maintain good health, both mentally and physically. As a result, I learnt that even the smallest step in the right direction can turn out to be the most important step of my life. Grow as a result of what I'm going through üòå

Nature bike rides were one of my favourite activities. While cycling, I found myself appreciating everything around me. Among all the grandeur of nature, I gain perspective and realise that my problems may not be as big as they appear to be. 

Another of my favourite activity would be weaving strings. It helped relieve stress and improve my mood. It helps stimulate self-reflection that occurs during the creative process, which can aid in the development of "psychological resilience‚Äù.

This trip has helped me become more grounded in the present moment rather than overthinking the past or what the future holds. It has also brought a positive impact on my overall health. Until now, I continue to use the digital wellbeing app @intellect.co to keep my wellbeing in check even after my stay.

@intellect.co @banyantreehotels @banyantreebintan #BanyanTreeHotels #wellbeingsanctuary #intellect #mentalhealth #mentalwellbeing

We are constantly bombarded with stimulation these days, with constant connectivity to others and the Internet.

I am most grateful for the experience that Banyan Tree Bintan has provided me. It gave me the time to be alone and helped me re-connect with myself and my body in the midst of Bintan‚Äôs idyllic landscape and natural beauty. Better yet, I was able to use the Intellect app, on this trip to record my feelings, thoughts, and other things that happened in my life. This helped me figure out patterns in my mood and general health üß† 

Being on this trip has helped me with coping with burnout and anxiety. I‚Äôve learnt how to deal with them by practicing mindfulness and self-awareness. Even when I‚Äôm back here in Singapore, I still do all of these things with the help of the intellect app, which lets me get help whenever I need it

growing up it was, ‚Äústay away from her‚Äù, ‚Äúmonster girl‚Äù, ‚Äúshe‚Äôs got eczema, don‚Äôt know if it‚Äôll spread‚Äù, & I remember always crying in primary school. I‚Äôve had staple bullets thrown in my face & hair, got kicked in the stomach, had my things thrown on the floor. I was always shy, withdrawn and afraid.

it got better when I grew older, & I wasn‚Äôt bullied anymore but I never ever let myself forget that ‚ÄúI wasn‚Äôt good enough‚Äù. it was ingrained deep down & I had low self esteem, no confidence, was insecure and hated absolutely everything about myself. 

‚Äúyou‚Äôre so ugly‚Äù‚Äùyou need to get plastic surgery‚Äù ‚Äúyou‚Äôre less than human‚Äù ‚Äúwhy can‚Äôt you be like everybody else‚Äù ‚Äúyour waist is too thick, why are your boobs so small‚Äù ‚Äúyour opinions don‚Äôt matter‚Äù the list of things I hated about myself only grew through the years & I picked myself apart daily and told myself that I wasn‚Äôt good enough. 

and yet now I‚Äôm doing all the things I once told myself that wasn‚Äôt possible for me. and yet now after I embraced my ‚Äúflaws‚Äù and learned to love myself, I‚Äôm being told that the things that I once hated & thought as flaws are desirable to others. my body or looks were never the problem, it was my thoughts. they were not flaws, this is who I am and I‚Äôm done hiding away and not saying what I want to say/ doing what I want. 

it was not easy getting here, I had a lot of help, and I‚Äôm still a work in progress but I‚Äôm so grateful for all the support. to all the amazing strong women out there, thank you for inspiring me & showing me strength.

HEALING ‚ù§Ô∏è‚Äçü©π

It‚Äôs been quite a journey for the past 6+ years.
I am really thankful for everything and every single one of you who are still here. 

I never thought healing would be so hard. I thought I was already in a better state of mind, I was confident that I‚Äôve recovered. But one day it hit me and I realised I am still the little girl that masked herself up so much that she hid everything at the corner of the room and walked out of it thinking she‚Äôs ready for the world. 

I thought going through 6 therapy sessions would suffice, I thought getting diagnosed and to be on medication would make me feel better.

Until I realised I need so much more time to heal and to recover from all the trauma for the past 18 years. 

And after so long, I finally decided that I need to take things slow and do everything I need to love myself correctly. 

To you, who have read till here, thank you so much for staying through. I hope I‚Äôll be here for long to continue sharing my healing life journey and real joy ü§ç

Back in art school, we have this class call <<grey matters>>. It forces you to think in between the colours, in between life - no right or wrong.

I remember vividly that there was once, our lecturer made us talk to plants and we had to write our conversation down.

There was another time, we were tasked to write every word that ran through our head. It‚Äôs like a verbal vomit and it felt really exciting. Because you can finally have a reason to do something imperfect yet true to yourself.

I strongly that believe life should be more like grey matters, to put aside what‚Äôs right or wrong, good or bad. Because whatever you do, there will be two sides of a coin // two or more different spectrum of possibilities // all kinds of perceptive üñ§

It's so crazy how cycling has changed my life. Living so close to the equator, a lot of us get up at 4:30am to start prepping for morning rides in order to avoid the blazing sun and heat here in Singapore. As a night owl, I find myself consciously trying to sleep earlier (still a WIP) these days. Which realistically, is better for my health anyway.

I‚Äôve also cut back on alcohol a lot in order to not feel like absolute garbage the next morning. Of course, I still love a cheeky drink (or 5) when I‚Äôm out with friends. But I definitely feel zero regrets saying no to booze when it‚Äôs a random Tues night dinner haha.

While I consider myself someone with discipline, I‚Äôve still felt so inspired by other cyclists and athletes who always show up to train, even when they don‚Äôt feel like it. That positive habit started rubbing off on me too & this translates into other aspects of life as well.

I‚Äôve recently revisited the lesson of indecisiveness because I found myself thinking a thousand thoughts, weighing the pros and cons, analysing the different outcomes, just to return to the initial stage of uncertainty where no actions are taken and no decisions are made. So I opened a spread of tarot cards for the millionth time for some advice, just to have them tell me it‚Äôs time to get out of my head ü•≤

Sure, I suppose it‚Äôs a good thing to practise evaluating our decisions. But I found myself being held captive by all the thoughts I‚Äôve came to form. And instead of having them help me with my decisions, I let them cripple me. 

I ended up in a position no better than where I started, except that I lost the most valuable thing I have ‚Äî time. Eventually, I learnt that at some point, I gotta let go of my need to know all the answers and just take action.

All those (over)thinking I did only served to delay a progress I‚Äôm meant to make. I realised I was holding myself back from finding out the real answers through experiencing because I wanted the answers before the experience. But life doesn‚Äôt work that way. So accept when it‚Äôs time for us to move on from thinking to doing. Because we can spend our entire lives thinking and ruminating and still not get any closer to materialising our dreams. How‚Äôs that for my own tarot reading üòÇüòÇüòÇ

Slow down. You don‚Äôt need to have all the answers and you don‚Äôt need to make all the decisions now. All you need to do is make one decision at a time, starting with what‚Äôs right in front of you ‚ù§Ô∏è And that‚Äôs all we need to do to keep moving forward.

I‚Äôve been thinking so much about what it takes to be an adult recently. 

Everyone has different dreams, makes different choices, and learns from different mistakes. Adulthood doesn‚Äôt always mean getting a house, having kids, getting your first car or heck, even getting married. But I‚Äôve come to realise that a big part of my journey in adulthood revolves around not only wanting to make my own decisions, but also to be able to make my own mistakes. Because our mistakes are our bearings to our goals. There are no unrecoverable mistakes, only new directions. So don‚Äôt let the fear or pressure of mistakes hold you back from the pursuit of your goals. Because the right decisions are blessings, and the mistakes are lessons ü§ç So whoever needs to hear this, you‚Äôre allowed to make mistakes ‚ú®

Last evening, President @halimahyacob appointed 102 Honorary Aides-De-Camp (HADCs) at the annual ADC Appointment Ceremony at the Istana. 31 HADCs from our Army, including 10 NSmen were appointed.

Apart from their primary appointments in our Army, the duties of the HADCs include assisting the President with the liaison and hosting of international dignitaries during State functions, ceremonies or events of ceremonial nature such Welcome Ceremonies and State Banquets. In addition, HADCs often organise and carry out State Events hosted by the President.

Distinctive of the ADCs are the thick, plaited cords parting at two separate points (i.e. aglets) on their right shoulder, termed as aiguillettes. The ADCs from the Singapore Armed Forces and the Singapore Civil Defence Force wear gold aiguillettes, while those from the Singapore Police Force wear silver aiguillettes.

Let us hear more from our HADCs!

Autumn; the beauty of letting go. üçÅüçÇ
We caught a really stunning sunset at #lakekinrin #ÈáëÈ±óÊπñ

The past few weeks haven't been the easiest. The anxiety - every single time my phone rings. The fear that each missed call/message from me leads to something worse that I will have to deal with. The guilt that no matter how much I try to be there whenever possible, it never seems to be enough. Feeling defeated and depleted, yet knowing that I can't fall.

Each time I feel like I really don't have the capacity to do more, I question myself if I can give more from my reserve tank.

At the same time, I came to realize that these days, I am more aware of mental and emotional well-being. So instead of allowing myself to be drained from constantly pouring from the empty cup, I would find opportunities to recharge - you know that feeling when you plug in the charger when the phone battery is at 1%, right before the phone shuts down? Self-care can come in the form of little things - like grabbing your favourite coffee, taking a long shower, buying your favourite snack, taking time off to do what you truly enjoy, etc - whatever self-care means to you and works for you.

I remember this very night when we headed out for our 10th Anniversary celebration. It was a time-off from everything else that I truly needed. I felt a sense of joy despite everything else that was happening - and allowed myself to immerse in that feeling while it lasted. #LittleWins moment for me.

To anyone else who has been feeling overwhelmed lately, I hope you will be able to sneak in some self-care moments and celebrate the little wins in your daily life. You've got this. ü§ç

A little tip and tap of our feet, the fun and silliness our romance is.

I‚Äôll trade you for nothing in this world, for your innocence and charm, matched nothing else like my simpleness.

You‚Äôd ask how did we, as the truth is, you already had me at that hello.

Made for this moment we are.

From our first encounter, the first text, the first date, the first kiss, this moment takes it all. 

The organ bellowed, the church bells chimed and there you are, veiled in white. 

Let me savour this moment, with the love of my life.

We tested our love across seasons and seas, but the destinations were not what we cared for.

A sense of belonging, a direction and a path to you, sang songs to me that you were indeed, home. 

I was never homesick again, when i made you my home.

Together is a wonderful place to be. Being with you didn‚Äôt correspond with reality, but it was so after all. 

Impassioned as much as we were for each other, we took our differences and acknowledged it. My strange little habits and appeals for things you‚Äôd never take a glance at, you took it with grace and acceptance. 

It‚Äôs our world after all, we built it and are proud of it.

‚ÄúBeing with you entailed the unknown. An adventure peppered with risks and hurdles to overcome. But with a leap of faith, i fell in to paradise, and into your arms. What comes next, is an adventure of life. Together, we‚Äôll sculpt our very adventure of a lifetime.‚Äù

One of the most witty and hilarious ones we had in front of our cameras. Their conversations and interactions got us cackling and pinching ourselves, but that‚Äôs just as genuine as they are. 

Being so authentic and unfeigned, were we only able to capture how endearing and sterling they held each other dearly to. 

Don‚Äôt be afraid to be and portray the fun and silliness in you.

Running, hand in hand, to the ends of the world. 

May the sun rise or set, with you by my side, will our strides align.

To the highs and lows, we‚Äôve been through it all. 

Together, through all walks of life.

What a magical sensation this is, a spin and a glance, the bits that I so adore. 

A mystery what time is, for what began with days and weeks, have became months and years. 

But with an embrace and a shimmer of daylight, tomorrow comes and we take on the world. 

Hence, a pocket of sunshine and hope, and here we go.

Documenting milestones. 

‚ÄúThe wheels on the bus goes round and round, round and round!‚Äù 
Elijah is a nimble and curious bundle of joy, inquisitively grasping anything he catches his eye on. Sam and her family could barely get his attention to focus on the camera, caroling to the ‚Äúwheels on the bus‚Äù as he wonders and explores his surrounding. His curious little stunts made us yield in laughter as we ponder upon the connections he makes through discovering this whole new world in front of him. 

As the little one grows inches, his crackles and punches gaining strength by the day, it‚Äôs incredible just how quickly they‚Äôre evolving from the day they were birthed. Besides the birthdays and the firsts of many things, the events where he learns or discovers something new, are equally fulfilling and worth celebrating for.

When two quiet and emotional souls come together to pledge their love and join in their journey forward.

The second of our Dearest Series

The confinement period may be a phase of recuperation that takes a toll on new mums and dads, as they brave through sleepless nights and postnatal blues; but as one battle through their first-time parenthood, it‚Äôs the little one‚Äôs kicks and struggles in his mid-afternoon slumber that tickles the soft spot in our hearts, that makes it all rewarding in itself, that makes it all worthwhile. 

Parental love is truly selfless, the magnitude of which that transcends above anything imaginable.

@omfgwen

Find yourself a partner who lifts you up, makes you feel good while being your safe haven all at the same time on days that you feel defeated. Someone who envelopes you with so much kindness and loves you beyond your aches, shortcomings and weaknesses for all of the days to come. 

Live, love and laugh. 
I think that‚Äôs all that matters in this life.

was an ordinary day.. I had my bridal make up trial in the afternoon, I jio-ed my best friend Jywa to come along with me. 
( I told her to come along 2 weeks in advance since she lived nearby) 

everything is normal during the make up trial, I ask Jywa what she wanted to eat because I was getting hungry.. she said "lets go to PS cafe at east coast" since she had to meet her boss to collect something at East Coast Park. 

After the bridal make up, usually I'm the one that would book a cab. But this time Jywa told me she booked already, Since her ‚ÄúBoss‚Äù would be paying for her cab fare.

I remember.. I was getting quite grumpy because we were at the north area we could have grab a bite in the north, why travel so far to the east?!! im so hungry already..

When we finally reached East Coast Park, I was 100% full make up on.... I was trying to hide from people even though I had mask on + I was wearing hilarious green shorts. oh my 

Then I saw a baby pink tent.. I was thinking so strange why is this tent in the middle of nowhere. thinking to myself " it could be a family having a picnic but they haven't arrived" Jywa told me to peep inside the tent I told her " no la its people tent ley" but being the nosy me i peep over a little and I saw BAGEL!! OMG that's where I knew this was MY PROPOSAL..

To be continued..in the video..

[üóíRecipe] No-bake, fuss-free, egg-free, alcohol-free, 10-min Cheat‚Äôs Tiramisu

Another lazy-ass recipe for lazy-ass brother. 

Difficulty level: -10/10
Deliciousity: 9/10
‚Äî
Ingredients
250ml heavy whipping cream
250g mascarpone cheese
50g sugar
1 tsp vanilla extract
~400ml black coffee/espresso
Lady fingers
Cocoa powder

1. Whisk up whipping cream, sugar, and vanilla extract until soft peaks. 
2. Whisk mascarpone cheese separately. 
3. Fold mascarpone cheese in to whipped cream mixture and whisk everything till well combined.
4. Layer and serve. Or chill it first if you have the self control to.

[üóíRecipe] Came up with a simple but really delicious recipe for Aglio Olio e Peperoncino‚Äîthe Italians call it AOP, we call it spicy aglio olio! Added two extra ingredients for a tinge of umami, and here‚Äôs the recipe using Barilla‚Äôs Spaghetti No.5:

Difficulty level: 6/10
Deliciousity: 8/10
Yield: Serves 2
Cooking time: 15 minutes

Ingredients
170g of Barilla Spaghetti No.5
¬º cup olive oil
¬º cup garlic, sliced
1 tbsp pepper flakes 
1 tbsp unsalted butter
1 tbsp shio kombu, chopped
8 prawns
Salt to cook pasta (7g for each litre of water)

Directions
1. Cook Barilla Spaghetti No.5 for 9 mins in a pot of salted boiling water.
2. Cook shelled prawns and set aside.
3. Using a cold pan on low heat, combine olive oil, sliced garlic, pepper flakes, and prawn heads. 
4. Discard prawn heads, and add spaghetti, half a ladle of pasta water, shio kombu, and cooked prawns into the pan.
5. Simmer on medium heat while stirring constantly. 
6. Finish the pasta with a knob of butter, tossing it until the sauce is creamy and emulsified. 
7. Garnish with parsley and a wedge of lemon for some acidity. Enjoy!
‚Äî
This recipe is made with Barilla pasta , the no.1 pasta brand in Italy that has been producing pasta for over 140 years. I am¬†glad to have time off¬†to rediscover and find peace with myself @ Banyan Tree Wellbeing Sanctuary. This experience has inspired me to look inward and become more aware of my daily actions, thoughts, and emotions. 

It is difficult to maintain good health, both mentally and physically. As a result, I learnt that even the smallest step in the right direction can turn out to be the most important step of my life. Grow as a result of what I'm going through üòå

Nature bike rides were one of my favourite activities. While cycling, I found myself appreciating everything around me. Among all the grandeur of nature, I gain perspective and realise that my problems may not be as big as they appear to be. 

Another of my favourite activity would be weaving strings. It helped relieve stress and improve my mood. It helps stimulate self-reflection that occurs during the creative process, which can aid in the development of "psychological resilience‚Äù.

This trip has helped me become more grounded in the present moment rather than overthinking the past or what the future holds. It has also brought a positive impact on my overall health. Until now, I continue to use the digital wellbeing app @intellect.co to keep my wellbeing in check even after my stay.

It gave me the time to be alone and helped me re-connect with myself and my body in the midst of Bintan‚Äôs idyllic landscape and natural beauty. Better yet, I was able to use the Intellect app, on this trip to record my feelings, thoughts, and other things that happened in my life. Being on this trip has helped me with coping with burnout and anxiety. I‚Äôve learnt how to deal with them by practicing mindfulness and self-awareness. almost a year ago, my makeup‚Äôs changed, I‚Äôve changed but still the same messy hair & sunburnt face ü§≠

growing up it was, ‚Äústay away from her‚Äù, ‚Äúmonster girl‚Äù, ‚Äúshe‚Äôs got eczema, don‚Äôt know if it‚Äôll spread‚Äù, & I remember always crying in primary school. I‚Äôve had staple bullets thrown in my face & hair, got kicked in the stomach, had my things thrown on the floor. I was always shy, withdrawn and afraid.

it got better when I grew older, & I wasn‚Äôt bullied anymore but I never ever let myself forget that ‚ÄúI wasn‚Äôt good enough‚Äù. it was ingrained deep down & I had low self esteem, no confidence, was insecure and hated absolutely everything about myself. 

‚Äúyou‚Äôre so ugly‚Äù‚Äùyou need to get plastic surgery‚Äù ‚Äúyou‚Äôre less than human‚Äù ‚Äúwhy can‚Äôt you be like everybody else‚Äù ‚Äúyour waist is too thick, why are your boobs so small‚Äù ‚Äúyour opinions don‚Äôt matter‚Äù the list of things I hated about myself only grew through the years & I picked myself apart daily and told myself that I wasn‚Äôt good enough. 

and yet now I‚Äôm doing all the things I once told myself that wasn‚Äôt possible for me. and yet now after I embraced my ‚Äúflaws‚Äù and learned to love myself, I‚Äôm being told that the things that I once hated & thought as flaws are desirable to others. my body or looks were never the problem, it was my thoughts. they were not flaws, this is who I am and I‚Äôm done hiding away and not saying what I want to say/ doing what I want. 

it was not easy getting here, I had a lot of help, and I‚Äôm still a work in progress but I‚Äôm so grateful for all the support. to all the amazing strong women out there, thank you for inspiring me & showing me strength.

happy international women‚Äôs day. ü§ç

It‚Äôs been quite a journey for the past 6+ years.

I never thought healing would be so hard. I thought I was already in a better state of mind, I was confident that I‚Äôve recovered. But one day it hit me and I realised I am still the little girl that masked herself up so much that she hid everything at the corner of the room and walked out of it thinking she‚Äôs ready for the world. 

I thought going through 6 therapy sessions would suffice, I thought getting diagnosed and to be on medication would make me feel better.

Until I realised I need so much more time to heal and to recover from all the trauma for the past 18 years. 

And after so long, I finally decided that I need to take things slow and do everything I need to love myself correctly.

Back in art school, we have this class call <<grey matters>>. It forces you to think in between the colours, in between life - no right or wrong.

I remember vividly that there was once, our lecturer made us talk to plants and we had to write our conversation down.

There was another time, we were tasked to write every word that ran through our head. It‚Äôs like a verbal vomit and it felt really exciting. Because you can finally have a reason to do something imperfect yet true to yourself.

I strongly that believe life should be more like grey matters, to put aside what‚Äôs right or wrong, good or bad. Because whatever you do, there will be two sides of a coin // two or more different spectrum of possibilities // all kinds of perceptive üñ§

If I‚Äôm ever friends with my mom, she‚Äôd definitely be that overprotective and rebellious sister that brings me everywhere. It‚Äôs gonna be a lot of chaos but a sisterhood filled with overflowing love. 

Happy birthday Cynthia üòò

It's so crazy how cycling has changed my life. Living so close to the equator, a lot of us get up at 4:30am to start prepping for morning rides in order to avoid the blazing sun and heat here in Singapore. As a night owl, I find myself consciously trying to sleep earlier (still a WIP) these days. Which realistically, is better for my health anyway.

I‚Äôve also cut back on alcohol a lot in order to not feel like absolute garbage the next morning. Of course, I still love a cheeky drink (or 5) when I‚Äôm out with friends. But I definitely feel zero regrets saying no to booze when it‚Äôs a random Tues night dinner haha.

While I consider myself someone with discipline, I‚Äôve still felt so inspired by other cyclists and athletes who always show up to train, even when they don‚Äôt feel like it. That positive habit started rubbing off on me too & this translates into other aspects of life as well.

‚Ä¢ 18% of the cyclists were females this year - which is already higher than before. I can‚Äôt help but feel like this number is just going to go up! I‚Äôve been thinking so much about what it takes to be an adult recently. 

Everyone has different dreams, makes different choices, and learns from different mistakes. Adulthood doesn‚Äôt always mean getting a house, having kids, getting your first car or heck, even getting married. But I‚Äôve come to realise that a big part of my journey in adulthood revolves around not only wanting to make my own decisions, but also to be able to make my own mistakes. Because our mistakes are our bearings to our goals. There are no unrecoverable mistakes, only new directions. So don‚Äôt let the fear or pressure of mistakes hold you back from the pursuit of your goals. Because the right decisions are blessings, and the mistakes are lessons ü§ç So whoever needs to hear this, you‚Äôre allowed to make mistakes ‚ú®

I‚Äôve recently revisited the lesson of indecisiveness because I found myself thinking a thousand thoughts, weighing the pros and cons, analysing the different outcomes, just to return to the initial stage of uncertainty where no actions are taken and no decisions are made. So I opened a spread of tarot cards for the millionth time for some advice, just to have them tell me it‚Äôs time to get out of my head ü•≤

Sure, I suppose it‚Äôs a good thing to practise evaluating our decisions. But I found myself being held captive by all the thoughts I‚Äôve came to form. And instead of having them help me with my decisions, I let them cripple me. 

I ended up in a position no better than where I started, except that I lost the most valuable thing I have ‚Äî time. Eventually, I learnt that at some point, I gotta let go of my need to know all the answers and just take action.

All those (over)thinking I did only served to delay a progress I‚Äôm meant to make. I realised I was holding myself back from finding out the real answers through experiencing because I wanted the answers before the experience. But life doesn‚Äôt work that way. So accept when it‚Äôs time for us to move on from thinking to doing. Because we can spend our entire lives thinking and ruminating and still not get any closer to materialising our dreams. Last evening, President @halimahyacob appointed 102 Honorary Aides-De-Camp (HADCs) at the annual ADC Appointment Ceremony at the Istana. 31 HADCs from our Army, including 10 NSmen were appointed.

Apart from their primary appointments in our Army, the duties of the HADCs include assisting the President with the liaison and hosting of international dignitaries during State functions, ceremonies or events of ceremonial nature such Welcome Ceremonies and State Banquets. In addition, HADCs often organise and carry out State Events hosted by the President.

Distinctive of the ADCs are the thick, plaited cords parting at two separate points (i.e. aglets) on their right shoulder, termed as aiguillettes. The ADCs from the Singapore Armed Forces and the Singapore Civil Defence Force wear gold aiguillettes, while those from the Singapore Police Force wear silver aiguillettes.

Let us hear more from our HADCs!

I'm definitely going to be back, now that their borders are reopening from 2nd May! I hope to be able to explore the South Island of New Zealand the next time. I've heard that it is arguably even more beautiful there. Anyone been?¬†

Not many people know this, but I have struggled with extremely dry, sensitive skin all my life. I remember noticing my scaly legs back when I was in Primary school, and I was quite ashamed of them then.

As an adult, I am still very conscious of this condition, and even though this is
not something I often talk about, it is something I am quite insecure about.

I OD on lotions and balms to cover-up the dry patches on bad skin days. My close friends know about this, and the lengths I go to to try to prevent it from getting worse - most avoid sharing a room with me on our girls trips as I switch off the air conditioner the minute we check in, and choose to sleep in the non-air conditioned room so as not to aggravate my dry skin. (Yes, I never sleep with the air conditioner turned on at home either!)

When Lion Japan approached me, I was amazed to find out that 66% of women in Singapore also struggle from sensitive skin! Who knew?

So happy that SunoHada has chosen to launch their first-ever skincare range for sensitive skin in Singapore. Developed with one of Japan's leading dermatologists, SunoHada, offers a gentle, yet effective 2-step daily routine for those of us with sensitive skin.

My favourite, and what I think is the ultimate gamechanger is an on-the-go mist that relives dry, itchy skin - in just 1 minute! I have one with me at all times in case I suddenly need it!

Try it for yourself k? Visit sunohada.com to get your complimentary sample kit today.

Autumn; the beauty of letting go. üçÅüçÇ
We caught a really stunning sunset at #lakekinrin #ÈáëÈ±óÊπñ

The past few weeks haven't been the easiest. The anxiety - every single time my phone rings. The fear that each missed call/message from me leads to something worse that I will have to deal with. The guilt that no matter how much I try to be there whenever possible, it never seems to be enough. Feeling defeated and depleted, yet knowing that I can't fall.

Each time I feel like I really don't have the capacity to do more, I question myself if I can give more from my reserve tank.

At the same time, I came to realize that these days, I am more aware of mental and emotional well-being. So instead of allowing myself to be drained from constantly pouring from the empty cup, I would find opportunities to recharge - you know that feeling when you plug in the charger when the phone battery is at 1%, right before the phone shuts down? Self-care can come in the form of little things - like grabbing your favourite coffee, taking a long shower, buying your favourite snack, taking time off to do what you truly enjoy, etc - whatever self-care means to you and works for you.

I remember this very night when we headed out for our 10th Anniversary celebration. It was a time-off from everything else that I truly needed. I felt a sense of joy despite everything else that was happening - and allowed myself to immerse in that feeling while it lasted. #LittleWins moment for me.

To anyone else who has been feeling overwhelmed lately, I hope you will be able to sneak in some self-care moments and celebrate the little wins in your daily life. You've got this. ü§ç

A little tip and tap of our feet, the fun and silliness our romance is.

I‚Äôll trade you for nothing in this world, for your innocence and charm, matched nothing else like my simpleness.

You‚Äôd ask how did we, as the truth is, you already had me at that hello.

Made for this moment we are.

From our first encounter, the first text, the first date, the first kiss, this moment takes it all. 

The organ bellowed, the church bells chimed and there you are, veiled in white. 

Let me savour this moment, with the love of my life.

We tested our love across seasons and seas, but the destinations were not what we cared for.

A sense of belonging, a direction and a path to you, sang songs to me that you were indeed, home. 

I was never homesick again, when i made you my home.

Together is a wonderful place to be. Being with you didn‚Äôt correspond with reality, but it was so after all. 

Impassioned as much as we were for each other, we took our differences and acknowledged it. My strange little habits and appeals for things you‚Äôd never take a glance at, you took it with grace and acceptance. 

It‚Äôs our world after all, we built it and are proud of it.

‚ÄúBeing with you entailed the unknown. An adventure peppered with risks and hurdles to overcome. But with a leap of faith, i fell in to paradise, and into your arms. What comes next, is an adventure of life. Together, we‚Äôll sculpt our very adventure of a lifetime.‚Äù

One of the most witty and hilarious ones we had in front of our cameras. Their conversations and interactions got us cackling and pinching ourselves, but that‚Äôs just as genuine as they are. 

Being so authentic and unfeigned, were we only able to capture how endearing and sterling they held each other dearly to. 

Don‚Äôt be afraid to be and portray the fun and silliness in you.

Running, hand in hand, to the ends of the world. 

May the sun rise or set, with you by my side, will our strides align.

To the highs and lows, we‚Äôve been through it all. 

Together, through all walks of life.

What a magical sensation this is, a spin and a glance, the bits that I so adore. 

A mystery what time is, for what began with days and weeks, have became months and years. 

But with an embrace and a shimmer of daylight, tomorrow comes and we take on the world. 

Hence, a pocket of sunshine and hope, and here we go.

Documenting milestones. 

‚ÄúThe wheels on the bus goes round and round, round and round!‚Äù 
Elijah is a nimble and curious bundle of joy, inquisitively grasping anything he catches his eye on. Sam and her family could barely get his attention to focus on the camera, caroling to the ‚Äúwheels on the bus‚Äù as he wonders and explores his surrounding. His curious little stunts made us yield in laughter as we ponder upon the connections he makes through discovering this whole new world in front of him. 

As the little one grows inches, his crackles and punches gaining strength by the day, it‚Äôs incredible just how quickly they‚Äôre evolving from the day they were birthed. Besides the birthdays and the firsts of many things, the events where he learns or discovers something new, are equally fulfilling and worth celebrating for.

When two quiet and emotional souls come together to pledge their love and join in their journey forward.

The second of our Dearest Series

The confinement period may be a phase of recuperation that takes a toll on new mums and dads, as they brave through sleepless nights and postnatal blues; but as one battle through their first-time parenthood, it‚Äôs the little one‚Äôs kicks and struggles in his mid-afternoon slumber that tickles the soft spot in our hearts, that makes it all rewarding in itself, that makes it all worthwhile. 

Parental love is truly selfless, the magnitude of which that transcends above anything imaginable.

@omfgwen

Find yourself a partner who lifts you up, makes you feel good while being your safe haven all at the same time on days that you feel defeated. Someone who envelopes you with so much kindness and loves you beyond your aches, shortcomings and weaknesses for all of the days to come. 

Live, love and laugh. 
I think that‚Äôs all that matters in this life.

11.03.21 
was an ordinary day.. I had my bridal make up trial in the afternoon, I jio-ed my best friend Jywa to come along with me. 
( I told her to come along 2 weeks in advance since she lived nearby) 

everything is normal during the make up trial, I ask Jywa what she wanted to eat because I was getting hungry.. she said "lets go to PS cafe at east coast" since she had to meet her boss to collect something at East Coast Park. 

After the bridal make up, usually I'm the one that would book a cab. But this time Jywa told me she booked already, Since her ‚ÄúBoss‚Äù would be paying for her cab fare.

I remember.. I was getting quite grumpy because we were at the north area we could have grab a bite in the north, why travel so far to the east?!! im so hungry already..

When we finally reached East Coast Park, I was 100% full make up on.... I was trying to hide from people even though I had mask on + I was wearing hilarious green shorts. oh my 

Then I saw a baby pink tent.. I was thinking so strange why is this tent in the middle of nowhere. thinking to myself " it could be a family having a picnic but they haven't arrived" Jywa told me to peep inside the tent I told her " no la its people tent ley" but being the nosy me i peep over a little and I saw BAGEL!! OMG that's where I knew this was MY PROPOSAL..

[üóíRecipe] No-bake, fuss-free, egg-free, alcohol-free, 10-min Cheat‚Äôs Tiramisu

Another lazy-ass recipe for lazy-ass brother. 

Difficulty level: -10/10
Deliciousity: 9/10
‚Äî
Ingredients
250ml heavy whipping cream
250g mascarpone cheese
50g sugar
1 tsp vanilla extract
~400ml black coffee/espresso
Lady fingers
Cocoa powder

1. Whisk up whipping cream, sugar, and vanilla extract until soft peaks. 
2. Whisk mascarpone cheese separately. 
3. Fold mascarpone cheese in to whipped cream mixture and whisk everything till well combined.
4. Layer and serve. Or chill it first if you have the self control to.

[üóíRecipe] Came up with a simple but really delicious recipe for Aglio Olio e Peperoncino‚Äîthe Italians call it AOP, we call it spicy aglio olio! Added two extra ingredients for a tinge of umami, and here‚Äôs the recipe using Barilla‚Äôs Spaghetti No.5:

Difficulty level: 6/10
Deliciousity: 8/10
Yield: Serves 2
Cooking time: 15 minutes

Ingredients
170g of Barilla Spaghetti No.5
¬º cup olive oil
¬º cup garlic, sliced
1 tbsp pepper flakes 
1 tbsp unsalted butter
1 tbsp shio kombu, chopped
8 prawns
Salt to cook pasta (7g for each litre of water)

Directions
1. Cook Barilla Spaghetti No.5 for 9 mins in a pot of salted boiling water.
2. Cook shelled prawns and set aside.
3. Using a cold pan on low heat, combine olive oil, sliced garlic, pepper flakes, and prawn heads. 
4. Discard prawn heads, and add spaghetti, half a ladle of pasta water, shio kombu, and cooked prawns into the pan.
5. Simmer on medium heat while stirring constantly. 
6. Finish the pasta with a knob of butter, tossing it until the sauce is creamy and emulsified. 
7. Garnish with parsley and a wedge of lemon for some acidity. Enjoy!
‚Äî
This recipe is made with Barilla pasta , the no.1 pasta brand in Italy that has been producing pasta for over 140 years.
